0:{"buildId":"MnqxQma7aQ7_7xDL-2evv","rsc":["$","$1","c",{"children":[["$","article",null,{"className":"bg-white","children":[["$","div",null,{"className":"max-w-4xl mx-auto px-4 sm:px-6 lg:px-8 pt-6","children":["$","nav",null,{"className":"flex items-center space-x-2 text-sm text-gray-600","children":[["$","$L2",null,{"href":"/","className":"hover:text-blue-600","children":"Home"}],[["$","div","/high-chairs",{"className":"flex items-center space-x-2","children":[["$","span",null,{"className":"text-gray-400","children":"/"}],["$","$L2",null,{"href":"/high-chairs","className":"hover:text-blue-600","children":"High Chairs"}]]}],["$","div","/high-chairs/when-to-start-using-a-high-chair",{"className":"flex items-center space-x-2","children":[["$","span",null,{"className":"text-gray-400","children":"/"}],["$","span",null,{"className":"text-gray-900 font-medium","children":"When to Start Using a High Chair: Developmental Readiness Guide"}]]}]]]}]}],["$","section",null,{"className":"max-w-4xl mx-auto px-4 sm:px-6 lg:px-8 py-12 border-b border-gray-200","children":[["$","h1",null,{"className":"text-4xl font-bold text-gray-900 mb-4","children":"When to Start Using a High Chair: Developmental Readiness Guide"}],["$","p",null,{"className":"text-lg text-gray-600","children":"Learn when babies are developmentally ready for high chairs, what signs indicate readiness, and how to transition from infant feeding to independent sitting."}]]}],["$","section",null,{"className":"max-w-4xl mx-auto px-4 sm:px-6 lg:px-8 py-12","children":["$","div",null,{"className":"prose prose-sm max-w-none","children":[["$","h2","0",{"className":"text-2xl font-bold text-gray-900 mt-8 mb-4","children":"Introduction"}],["$","p","1",{"className":"text-gray-700 mb-4 leading-relaxed","children":"The question \"When should my baby sit in a high chair?\" has no single answer—readiness depends on developmental milestones, not just age. Some babies are ready at 4 months; others need to wait until 8-9 months. Starting too early risks falls and frustration. Waiting too long misses developmental benefits. This guide walks through the signs of readiness, the progression from infant feeding to high chair eating, and how to time the transition successfully."}],["$","h2","2",{"className":"text-2xl font-bold text-gray-900 mt-8 mb-4","children":"Developmental Milestones That Matter"}],["$","p","3",{"className":"text-gray-700 mb-4 leading-relaxed","children":"High chair readiness requires three overlapping skills: (1) sitting with minimal support, (2) coordinating hand-to-mouth movements, and (3) showing interest in food. Let's examine each."}],["$","h2","4",{"className":"text-2xl font-bold text-gray-900 mt-8 mb-4","children":"# Sitting Skills"}],["$","p","5",{"className":"text-gray-700 mb-4 leading-relaxed","children":"By 4 months, babies begin to sit with complete support (adult holding them upright). By 6 months, most babies can sit with trunk support (a pillow behind them) but still need balance assistance. By 7-8 months, babies can sit without support for 30+ seconds. By 9+ months, sitting independently is automatic."}],["$","p","6",{"className":"text-gray-700 mb-4 leading-relaxed","children":"**Why this matters:** A high chair's primary job is to hold your baby upright during meals. If your baby cannot maintain sitting posture—even briefly—a high chair becomes frustrating. The baby slumps, feels confined, and may resist the chair entirely."}],["$","p","7",{"className":"text-gray-700 mb-4 leading-relaxed","children":"**Readiness signal:** Your baby sits with minimal support (pillow assistance is fine) for at least 1-2 minutes without tipping or flopping sideways."}],["$","h2","8",{"className":"text-2xl font-bold text-gray-900 mt-8 mb-4","children":"# Hand-to-Mouth Coordination"}],"$L3","$L4","$L5","$L6","$L7","$L8","$L9","$La","$Lb","$Lc","$Ld","$Le","$Lf","$L10","$L11","$L12","$L13","$L14","$L15","$L16","$L17","$L18","$L19","$L1a","$L1b","$L1c","$L1d","$L1e","$L1f","$L20","$L21","$L22","$L23","$L24","$L25","$L26","$L27","$L28","$L29","$L2a","$L2b","$L2c","$L2d","$L2e","$L2f","$L30","$L31","$L32","$L33","$L34","$L35","$L36","$L37","$L38","$L39","$L3a","$L3b","$L3c","$L3d","$L3e","$L3f","$L40","$L41","$L42","$L43","$L44","$L45","$L46","$L47"]}]}],"$L48","$L49","$L4a"]}],["$L4b"],"$L4c"]}],"loading":null,"isPartial":false}
3:["$","p","9",{"className":"text-gray-700 mb-4 leading-relaxed","children":"By 5-6 months, babies develop the coordination to move their hands to their mouth intentionally (called the \"raking grasp\"). By 6-7 months, the grasp refines into a pincer grip (thumb and finger). By 8-9 months, the pincer grip is strong and controlled."}]
4:["$","p","10",{"className":"text-gray-700 mb-4 leading-relaxed","children":"This skill is essential because high chairs are most useful when your baby can feed themselves finger foods or hold a spoon. If feeding requires complete adult hand-feeding, a high chair offers less advantage over feeding your baby in your arms."}]
5:["$","p","11",{"className":"text-gray-700 mb-4 leading-relaxed","children":"**Readiness signal:** Your baby reaches for and grasps objects intentionally and brings them to their mouth without prompting."}]
6:["$","h2","12",{"className":"text-2xl font-bold text-gray-900 mt-8 mb-4","children":"# Food Interest and Readiness"}]
7:["$","p","13",{"className":"text-gray-700 mb-4 leading-relaxed","children":"The American Academy of Pediatrics (AAP) defines readiness for solid foods (relevant to high chair use) as:"}]
8:["$","ol","14",{"className":"list-decimal list-inside space-y-2 text-gray-700 mb-4","children":[["$","li","0",{"children":"Sitting upright with minimal support"}],["$","li","1",{"children":"Loss of the extrusion reflex (tongue-thrust that pushes food out)"}],["$","li","2",{"children":"Interest in food (reaching for it, watching others eat, opening mouth when food approaches)"}],["$","li","3",{"children":"Around 6 months of age (though this is a general guideline, not a hard rule)"}]]}]
9:["$","p","15",{"className":"text-gray-700 mb-4 leading-relaxed","children":"**Readiness signal:** Your baby watches you eat with visible interest, reaches for your food or utensils, and opens their mouth when a spoon approaches."}]
a:["$","h2","16",{"className":"text-2xl font-bold text-gray-900 mt-8 mb-4","children":"The Readiness Timeline"}]
b:["$","h2","17",{"className":"text-2xl font-bold text-gray-900 mt-8 mb-4","children":"# 4-5 Months: Probably Not Ready"}]
c:["$","p","18",{"className":"text-gray-700 mb-4 leading-relaxed","children":"At 4-5 months, most babies sit only with complete support and lack the hand-to-mouth coordination needed for a high chair. Feeding is exclusively breast or bottle. High chairs are premature."}]
d:["$","p","19",{"className":"text-gray-700 mb-4 leading-relaxed","children":"**Exception:** If your baby sits well with minimal support at 4 months (unusual but possible), you can introduce the high chair for very short periods—minutes only—to familiarize your baby with the setting without pressure."}]
e:["$","h2","20",{"className":"text-2xl font-bold text-gray-900 mt-8 mb-4","children":"# 6 Months: Maybe Ready (Case-by-Case)"}]
f:["$","p","21",{"className":"text-gray-700 mb-4 leading-relaxed","children":"At 6 months, many babies show the developmental signs above, though readiness varies widely. Some 6-month-olds sit unsupported and reach for food; others are still months away."}]
10:["$","p","22",{"className":"text-gray-700 mb-4 leading-relaxed","children":"**How to assess:** Place your baby in a high chair with a pillow for support. Does your baby feel secure? Does your baby show discomfort, frustration, or genuine interest? A baby ready at 6 months usually smiles, looks around, and accepts the position. A baby not ready will fuss, arch their back, or seem uncomfortable."}]
11:["$","p","23",{"className":"text-gray-700 mb-4 leading-relaxed","children":"**First-time introduction protocol at 6 months:**"}]
12:["$","ol","24",{"className":"list-decimal list-inside space-y-2 text-gray-700 mb-4","children":[["$","li","0",{"children":"Assemble and position the high chair in your kitchen, where your family eats"}],["$","li","1",{"children":"Place your baby in the chair for 2-3 minutes while you sit nearby"}],["$","li","2",{"children":"Offer no food yet—just familiarization with the setting"}],["$","li","3",{"children":"If your baby is calm or curious, repeat every other day for a week"}],["$","li","4",{"children":"Once your baby is comfortable, introduce a single soft food (infant cereal mixed with breast milk or formula)"}]]}]
13:["$","p","25",{"className":"text-gray-700 mb-4 leading-relaxed","children":"If your baby cries, arches, or resists strongly, wait another month. Forcing the high chair at an early stage creates negative associations."}]
14:["$","h2","26",{"className":"text-2xl font-bold text-gray-900 mt-8 mb-4","children":"# 7-8 Months: Usually Ready"}]
15:["$","p","27",{"className":"text-gray-700 mb-4 leading-relaxed","children":"By 7-8 months, most babies sit independently, coordinate hand-to-mouth movements, and show clear interest in food. The timing aligns with the introduction of solid foods."}]
16:["$","p","28",{"className":"text-gray-700 mb-4 leading-relaxed","children":"At this stage, high chair use becomes practical: your baby sits safely while you offer finger foods or spoon-feed gradually. The baby can begin to participate (grabbing utensils, reaching for food) rather than being a passive recipient."}]
17:["$","p","29",{"className":"text-gray-700 mb-4 leading-relaxed","children":"**Integration at 7-8 months:**"}]
18:["$","ul","30",{"className":"list-disc list-inside space-y-2 text-gray-700 mb-4","children":[["$","li","0",{"children":"Position the high chair at the dining table where your family eats"}],["$","li","1",{"children":"Offer soft finger foods (mashed banana, avocado, cooked vegetables) alongside breast/bottle feeds"}],["$","li","2",{"children":"Let your baby grasp and mouth foods, exploring tastes and textures"}],["$","li","3",{"children":"Your baby may swallow, may spit out, or may just mouth without swallowing—all are normal"}],["$","li","4",{"children":"Meals last 10-15 minutes; duration increases gradually"}]]}]
19:["$","h2","31",{"className":"text-2xl font-bold text-gray-900 mt-8 mb-4","children":"# 9+ Months: Definitely Ready"}]
1a:["$","p","32",{"className":"text-gray-700 mb-4 leading-relaxed","children":"By 9 months, nearly all babies sit independently, grasp and release objects, and eat soft finger foods actively. High chair use is seamless. Meals become a social family event—your baby sits with you, explores food, and participates in eating rituals."}]
1b:["$","h2","33",{"className":"text-2xl font-bold text-gray-900 mt-8 mb-4","children":"The Progression From Bottle/Breast to High Chair Eating"}]
1c:["$","h2","34",{"className":"text-2xl font-bold text-gray-900 mt-8 mb-4","children":"# Phase 1: Bottle/Breast + Chair Familiarization (4-6 Months)"}]
1d:["$","p","35",{"className":"text-gray-700 mb-4 leading-relaxed","children":"Your baby's nutrition is 100% from breast or bottle. The high chair is an introduction: your baby sits briefly while you read, talk, or prepare food. No food is offered. The goal is comfort with the chair's presence and position."}]
1e:["$","p","36",{"className":"text-gray-700 mb-4 leading-relaxed","children":"**Duration:** 2-5 minutes per day\n**Feeding method:** Breast or bottle\n**High chair role:** Sitting practice, familiarization"}]
1f:["$","h2","37",{"className":"text-2xl font-bold text-gray-900 mt-8 mb-4","children":"# Phase 2: Introduction to Solids + High Chair Meals (6-7 Months)"}]
20:["$","p","38",{"className":"text-gray-700 mb-4 leading-relaxed","children":"You introduce iron-fortified infant cereal mixed with breast milk or formula, fed by spoon. Your baby sits in the high chair during this feeding. The chair transitions from \"sitting practice\" to \"eating location.\""}]
21:["$","p","39",{"className":"text-gray-700 mb-4 leading-relaxed","children":"**Typical progression:**\n- Start: 1-2 tablespoons of cereal once daily\n- Increase: Add vegetables or fruits after 3-5 days of cereal-only\n- Frequency: Once daily for 2 weeks, then twice daily"}]
22:["$","p","40",{"className":"text-gray-700 mb-4 leading-relaxed","children":"**Duration:** 10-20 minutes per meal\n**Feeding method:** Spoon (adult-fed)\n**High chair role:** Mealtime seating"}]
23:["$","h2","41",{"className":"text-2xl font-bold text-gray-900 mt-8 mb-4","children":"# Phase 3: Finger Foods + Self-Feeding Practice (7-9 Months)"}]
24:["$","p","42",{"className":"text-gray-700 mb-4 leading-relaxed","children":"Your baby transitions from spoon-fed purees to finger foods. The high chair becomes a platform for exploration: your baby grasps soft foods, mouths them, and learns self-feeding."}]
25:["$","p","43",{"className":"text-gray-700 mb-4 leading-relaxed","children":"**Foods introduced:**\n- Cooked vegetables (carrots, sweet potato, green beans) in soft, bite-sized pieces\n- Soft fruits (mashed banana, avocado, peach)\n- Cottage cheese, yogurt, mashed beans\n- Soft bread or pasta"}]
26:["$","p","44",{"className":"text-gray-700 mb-4 leading-relaxed","children":"**Duration:** 15-30 minutes per meal (slower due to self-feeding exploration)\n**Feeding method:** Mix of spoon-fed and self-fed finger foods\n**High chair role:** Active mealtime participant, self-feeding practice"}]
27:["$","h2","45",{"className":"text-2xl font-bold text-gray-900 mt-8 mb-4","children":"# Phase 4: Table Foods + Family Meals (9+ Months)"}]
28:["$","p","46",{"className":"text-gray-700 mb-4 leading-relaxed","children":"Your baby eats modified versions of family meals (softer, no added salt, no honey, choking hazards removed). The high chair is where family eating happens—you, your partner, and your baby all eat together."}]
29:["$","p","47",{"className":"text-gray-700 mb-4 leading-relaxed","children":"**Foods offered:**\n- Soft cooked vegetables and fruits from family dinner\n- Cooked pasta, rice, bread\n- Ground or shredded cooked meat\n- Eggs, cheese, beans\n- Gradually moving toward regular family foods with age-appropriate adjustments"}]
2a:["$","p","48",{"className":"text-gray-700 mb-4 leading-relaxed","children":"**Duration:** 20-40 minutes per meal (family meal-paced)\n**Feeding method:** Mostly self-fed, with spoon assistance as needed\n**High chair role:** Family mealtime integration"}]
2b:["$","h2","49",{"className":"text-2xl font-bold text-gray-900 mt-8 mb-4","children":"Addressing Common Readiness Questions"}]
2c:["$","h2","50",{"className":"text-2xl font-bold text-gray-900 mt-8 mb-4","children":"# \"My baby is 6 months old but sits well. Is it too early?\""}]
2d:["$","p","51",{"className":"text-gray-700 mb-4 leading-relaxed","children":"If your baby sits independently and shows food interest (reaching, opening mouth, watching you eat), starting at 6 months is reasonable. However, watch for signs of readiness, not just age. Some 6-month-olds are genuinely ready; others aren't until 8 months. Follow your baby's cues, not the calendar."}]
2e:["$","h2","52",{"className":"text-2xl font-bold text-gray-900 mt-8 mb-4","children":"# \"My baby hates the high chair. Should I force it?\""}]
2f:["$","p","53",{"className":"text-gray-700 mb-4 leading-relaxed","children":"No. Forcing a baby into a high chair before readiness creates negative associations. If your baby is miserable, step back. Try again in 2-3 weeks. In the meantime, feed your baby on your lap or in a bouncer. High chairs are tools, not requirements—if your baby resists, the timing is off."}]
30:["$","h2","54",{"className":"text-2xl font-bold text-gray-900 mt-8 mb-4","children":"# \"My baby is 10+ months and still prefers my lap. Is something wrong?\""}]
31:["$","p","55",{"className":"text-gray-700 mb-4 leading-relaxed","children":"No. Some babies are happier fed on a parent's lap longer. If your baby eats well, gains weight, and shows no feeding difficulties, feeding on your lap is fine. The high chair will be available when your baby is ready. Forced independence often backfires."}]
32:["$","h2","56",{"className":"text-2xl font-bold text-gray-900 mt-8 mb-4","children":"# \"Should I get a high chair before my baby is ready?\""}]
33:["$","p","57",{"className":"text-gray-700 mb-4 leading-relaxed","children":"It's reasonable to purchase a high chair at 4-5 months and assemble it before you need it. This avoids last-minute shopping. However, don't introduce your baby to the chair until you see readiness signs. An assembled-but-unused high chair in your kitchen is fine; a baby forced into an inappropriate chair is not."}]
34:["$","h2","58",{"className":"text-2xl font-bold text-gray-900 mt-8 mb-4","children":"Selecting the Right Chair for Your Baby's Readiness Stage"}]
35:["$","h2","59",{"className":"text-2xl font-bold text-gray-900 mt-8 mb-4","children":"# If Introducing at 6 Months"}]
36:["$","p","60",{"className":"text-gray-700 mb-4 leading-relaxed","children":"Choose a chair with:\n- **Excellent back support** - Your baby may not sit fully independently, so back cushioning matters\n- **Adjustable recline** - Some 6-month-olds still have a slight recline preference\n- **Generous arm space** - Room for a support pillow if needed\n- **Low height minimum** - Ensures your baby's feet can rest on a footrest or base (important for comfort)"}]
37:["$","p","61",{"className":"text-gray-700 mb-4 leading-relaxed","children":"**Best choices:** Graco Blossom (5-position recline), Chicco Polly 2Start (6-position recline), Nuna ZAAZ (2-position recline)"}]
38:["$","h2","62",{"className":"text-2xl font-bold text-gray-900 mt-8 mb-4","children":"# If Introducing at 7-8 Months"}]
39:["$","p","63",{"className":"text-gray-700 mb-4 leading-relaxed","children":"Choose a chair with:\n- **5-point harness** - Your baby is mobile and may try to escape\n- **Removable, dishwasher-safe tray** - You'll clean the tray frequently\n- **Easy seat adjustment** - Height adjustment matters as your baby grows\n- **Stable base** - Your baby will wiggle and bounce; stability prevents tipping"}]
3a:["$","p","64",{"className":"text-gray-700 mb-4 leading-relaxed","children":"**Best choices:** UPPAbaby Ciro, OXO Sprout, Stokke Tripp Trapp (for convertible long-term use)"}]
3b:["$","h2","65",{"className":"text-2xl font-bold text-gray-900 mt-8 mb-4","children":"# If Introducing at 9+ Months"}]
3c:["$","p","66",{"className":"text-gray-700 mb-4 leading-relaxed","children":"Choose a chair with:\n- **5-point harness** - Your baby is active; restraint is essential\n- **Easy-clean surfaces** - Feeding is messy; wipeable materials are valuable\n- **Convertible growth potential** - If you want years of use, convertible chairs ($300+) grow with your child; full-size chairs ($100-$300) work for toddler years only"}]
3d:["$","p","67",{"className":"text-gray-700 mb-4 leading-relaxed","children":"**Best choices:** Any of the premium convertibles (Stokke, UPPAbaby, Nuna) or budget-friendly Joovy Nook or IKEA Antilop"}]
3e:["$","h2","68",{"className":"text-2xl font-bold text-gray-900 mt-8 mb-4","children":"Signs Your Baby Is Truly Not Ready"}]
3f:["$","p","69",{"className":"text-gray-700 mb-4 leading-relaxed","children":"Delay introducing a high chair if your baby:"}]
40:["$","ul","70",{"className":"list-disc list-inside space-y-2 text-gray-700 mb-4","children":[["$","li","0",{"children":"Cannot sit upright with any amount of support (less than 6 months for most babies)"}],["$","li","1",{"children":"Cries, arches, or resists the seated position consistently"}],["$","li","2",{"children":"Has not lost the extrusion reflex (food spills out of the mouth immediately)"}],["$","li","3",{"children":"Shows no interest in food or eating"}],["$","li","4",{"children":"Is significantly underweight or has feeding difficulties (consult your pediatrician)"}]]}]
41:["$","p","71",{"className":"text-gray-700 mb-4 leading-relaxed","children":"Forcing high chair use on a baby who's not ready wastes everyone's time and energy. Waiting 4-6 weeks until readiness emerges is worth it."}]
42:["$","h2","72",{"className":"text-2xl font-bold text-gray-900 mt-8 mb-4","children":"Transitioning Out of High Chairs"}]
43:["$","p","73",{"className":"text-gray-700 mb-4 leading-relaxed","children":"Most children outgrow high chairs between ages 2.5 and 3.5 years. Signs include consistent climbing out, requests to sit in regular chairs, and approaching the weight limit. The transition is to a booster seat (a removable tray chair that attaches to regular dining chairs) or a regular chair with a cushion."}]
44:["$","p","74",{"className":"text-gray-700 mb-4 leading-relaxed","children":"This transition is also age-appropriate—by 2.5-3 years, children have the sitting skills and understanding to follow basic safety instructions (\"Sit still while we eat\")."}]
45:["$","h2","75",{"className":"text-2xl font-bold text-gray-900 mt-8 mb-4","children":"Key Takeaways"}]
46:["$","p","76",{"className":"text-gray-700 mb-4 leading-relaxed","children":"Readiness for high chairs is driven by developmental milestones (independent sitting, hand-to-mouth coordination, food interest), not age alone. While 6-7 months is common, some babies are ready at 4-5 months; others need to wait until 8-9 months. Watch your baby, not the calendar. Introduction should be gradual and pressure-free. If your baby dislikes the chair, pause for a few weeks and try again—forced feeding and seating create negative associations that persist for years."}]
47:["$","p","77",{"className":"text-gray-700 mb-4 leading-relaxed","children":"The progression from bottle/breast to high chair eating typically takes 6-12 months, moving from spoon-fed purees to finger foods to family meal participation. This gradual shift allows your baby to learn eating skills in a safe, supportive environment. Your role is to offer food, support exploration, and ensure safety—not to force eating or complete consumption. Mealtimes should be positive, social events that your family enjoys together."}]
48:["$","section",null,{"className":"max-w-4xl mx-auto px-4 sm:px-6 lg:px-8 py-12 border-t border-gray-200","children":[["$","h2",null,{"className":"text-2xl font-bold text-gray-900 mb-6","children":"More High Chair Resources"}],["$","div",null,{"className":"grid grid-cols-1 md:grid-cols-2 gap-4","children":[["$","$L2",null,{"href":"/high-chairs","className":"p-4 border border-gray-200 rounded-lg hover:shadow-md transition-shadow","children":[["$","h3",null,{"className":"font-bold text-gray-900 mb-2","children":"Back to Comparison"}],["$","p",null,{"className":"text-sm text-gray-600","children":"View all 13 high chairs with interactive filters and ratings."}]]}],["$","$L2",null,{"href":"/high-chairs/best-high-chairs-for-small-spaces","className":"p-4 border border-gray-200 rounded-lg hover:shadow-md transition-shadow","children":[["$","h3",null,{"className":"font-bold text-gray-900 mb-2","children":"Small Spaces Guide"}],["$","p",null,{"className":"text-sm text-gray-600","children":"Find compact and foldable options for apartments and tiny homes."}]]}],["$","$L2",null,{"href":"/high-chairs/wooden-vs-plastic-high-chairs","className":"p-4 border border-gray-200 rounded-lg hover:shadow-md transition-shadow","children":[["$","h3",null,{"className":"font-bold text-gray-900 mb-2","children":"Materials Comparison"}],["$","p",null,{"className":"text-sm text-gray-600","children":"Compare wood and plastic for durability, cleaning, and aesthetics."}]]}],["$","$L2",null,{"href":"/high-chairs/high-chair-safety-checklist","className":"p-4 border border-gray-200 rounded-lg hover:shadow-md transition-shadow","children":[["$","h3",null,{"className":"font-bold text-gray-900 mb-2","children":"Safety Guide"}],["$","p",null,{"className":"text-sm text-gray-600","children":"Learn harness types, stability testing, and recall information."}]]}]]}]]}]
49:["$","section",null,{"className":"max-w-4xl mx-auto px-4 sm:px-6 lg:px-8 py-8 border-t border-gray-200","children":["$","p",null,{"className":"text-xs text-gray-500","children":"This article was prepared with AI-assisted research. It is provided for informational purposes only and does not constitute medical, safety, or product advice. All information should be independently verified before use. We may earn affiliate commissions from Amazon purchases made through links in this article."}]}]
